[{"text": "in this video we're going to talk about", "start": 1.439, "duration": 5.201}, {"text": "ammeters and voltmeters", "start": 2.879, "duration": 5.441}, {"text": "now if you want to measure", "start": 6.64, "duration": 3.6}, {"text": "the current in a circuit", "start": 8.32, "duration": 4.479}, {"text": "you want to use an ammeter", "start": 10.24, "duration": 4.319}, {"text": "and the symbol for that", "start": 12.799, "duration": 4.081}, {"text": "is an a in a circle if you want to", "start": 14.559, "duration": 3.921}, {"text": "measure the voltage", "start": 16.88, "duration": 3.28}, {"text": "across the device you need to use a", "start": 18.48, "duration": 3.28}, {"text": "voltmeter", "start": 20.16, "duration": 4.64}, {"text": "with the symbol v", "start": 21.76, "duration": 5.679}, {"text": "so let's say if", "start": 24.8, "duration": 4.0}, {"text": "you have a resistor and you want to", "start": 27.439, "duration": 2.801}, {"text": "calculate the voltage across the", "start": 28.8, "duration": 2.719}, {"text": "resistor", "start": 30.24, "duration": 3.36}, {"text": "you need to connect the voltmeter across", "start": 31.519, "duration": 3.441}, {"text": "the resistor", "start": 33.6, "duration": 3.2}, {"text": "now if you want to calculate the current", "start": 34.96, "duration": 3.68}, {"text": "flowing in a circuit", "start": 36.8, "duration": 4.079}, {"text": "you need to connect the ammeter in", "start": 38.64, "duration": 4.8}, {"text": "series with the resistor", "start": 40.879, "duration": 3.68}, {"text": "if you want to calculate the current", "start": 43.44, "duration": 3.84}, {"text": "flowing through the resistor", "start": 44.559, "duration": 5.121}, {"text": "so keep that in mind with an ammeter if", "start": 47.28, "duration": 4.56}, {"text": "you want to measure the current of a", "start": 49.68, "duration": 4.399}, {"text": "device you need to connect it in series", "start": 51.84, "duration": 4.0}, {"text": "with such a device", "start": 54.079, "duration": 3.681}, {"text": "and if you want to measure the voltage", "start": 55.84, "duration": 4.0}, {"text": "you need to connect a voltmeter in", "start": 57.76, "duration": 5.36}, {"text": "parallel with such a device", "start": 59.84, "duration": 6.24}, {"text": "or across the device", "start": 63.12, "duration": 5.2}, {"text": "now when designing an ammeter", "start": 66.08, "duration": 4.16}, {"text": "you want the internal resistance to be", "start": 68.32, "duration": 3.28}, {"text": "very very low", "start": 70.24, "duration": 3.68}, {"text": "ideally very close to zero", "start": 71.6, "duration": 4.48}, {"text": "because you don't want the ammeter to", "start": 73.92, "duration": 3.92}, {"text": "affect the current flowing in the", "start": 76.08, "duration": 3.679}, {"text": "circuit because that's going to defeat", "start": 77.84, "duration": 3.599}, {"text": "the purpose of measuring", "start": 79.759, "duration": 3.68}, {"text": "the current in the circuit in the case", "start": 81.439, "duration": 4.0}, {"text": "of a voltmeter you want the internal", "start": 83.439, "duration": 4.561}, {"text": "resistance to be very very high", "start": 85.439, "duration": 4.32}, {"text": "very close to infinity", "start": 88.0, "duration": 3.759}, {"text": "so that the voltmeter", "start": 89.759, "duration": 4.161}, {"text": "doesn't decrease the voltage", "start": 91.759, "duration": 4.561}, {"text": "across the resistor to any significant", "start": 93.92, "duration": 4.48}, {"text": "extent", "start": 96.32, "duration": 3.839}, {"text": "so you want the resistance to be let's", "start": 98.4, "duration": 4.64}, {"text": "say like 10 to the 7", "start": 100.159, "duration": 5.121}, {"text": "ohms which is like 10 mega ohms or", "start": 103.04, "duration": 4.079}, {"text": "higher", "start": 105.28, "duration": 3.6}, {"text": "let's work on a problem that shows how a", "start": 107.119, "duration": 5.36}, {"text": "galvanometer can be used as an ammeter", "start": 108.88, "duration": 5.76}, {"text": "now this particular galvanometer has a", "start": 112.479, "duration": 5.041}, {"text": "full scale sensitivity of 200", "start": 114.64, "duration": 5.6}, {"text": "microamps", "start": 117.52, "duration": 2.72}, {"text": "so let's say if", "start": 120.96, "duration": 6.0}, {"text": "this is the display of the galvanometer", "start": 122.799, "duration": 6.32}, {"text": "in the middle it would have a reading of", "start": 126.96, "duration": 4.72}, {"text": "0 microamps", "start": 129.119, "duration": 4.241}, {"text": "at full deflection", "start": 131.68, "duration": 3.52}, {"text": "it's going to be 200", "start": 133.36, "duration": 3.68}, {"text": "microamps", "start": 135.2, "duration": 4.64}, {"text": "and on the left side", "start": 137.04, "duration": 5.199}, {"text": "negative 200 microamps", "start": 139.84, "duration": 5.28}, {"text": "if you reverse the polarity", "start": 142.239, "duration": 4.64}, {"text": "now what we want to do is we want to", "start": 145.12, "duration": 3.44}, {"text": "design an ammeter", "start": 146.879, "duration": 2.561}, {"text": "where", "start": 148.56, "duration": 3.759}, {"text": "it can read 0 to 10 amps", "start": 149.44, "duration": 4.96}, {"text": "so this would be a current of 0", "start": 152.319, "duration": 4.0}, {"text": "but instead of 200 microamps this would", "start": 154.4, "duration": 4.72}, {"text": "represent a current of 10 amps", "start": 156.319, "duration": 5.681}, {"text": "so how can we do that", "start": 159.12, "duration": 2.88}, {"text": "so first you need a shunt resistor", "start": 165.68, "duration": 4.72}, {"text": "and across that", "start": 168.48, "duration": 3.119}, {"text": "is", "start": 170.4, "duration": 2.96}, {"text": "the galvanometer", "start": 171.599, "duration": 5.041}, {"text": "represented by the symbol g", "start": 173.36, "duration": 3.28}, {"text": "so that's the shunt resistor capital r", "start": 176.72, "duration": 5.28}, {"text": "lowercase r is the eternal resistance", "start": 179.2, "duration": 3.64}, {"text": "of the", "start": 182.0, "duration": 2.8}, {"text": "galvanometer", "start": 182.84, "duration": 4.679}, {"text": "so this picture combined represents the", "start": 184.8, "duration": 5.12}, {"text": "ammeter", "start": 187.519, "duration": 4.561}, {"text": "and so the current that's being measured", "start": 189.92, "duration": 3.36}, {"text": "flows", "start": 192.08, "duration": 3.519}, {"text": "at this point", "start": 193.28, "duration": 3.76}, {"text": "and the current that flows through the", "start": 195.599, "duration": 4.881}, {"text": "resistor r we're going to call it ir", "start": 197.04, "duration": 5.52}, {"text": "and then", "start": 200.48, "duration": 3.6}, {"text": "the current that flows through the", "start": 202.56, "duration": 4.64}, {"text": "galvanometer we'll call it ig", "start": 204.08, "duration": 5.12}, {"text": "so i is the sum of", "start": 207.2, "duration": 3.28}, {"text": "ir", "start": 209.2, "duration": 3.92}, {"text": "plus ig", "start": 210.48, "duration": 4.319}, {"text": "now the maximum current that the", "start": 213.12, "duration": 3.759}, {"text": "galvanometer can accept", "start": 214.799, "duration": 4.241}, {"text": "at full deflection", "start": 216.879, "duration": 7.28}, {"text": "is 200 microamps so that's equal to ig", "start": 219.04, "duration": 6.479}, {"text": "and when it receives that amount of", "start": 224.159, "duration": 2.881}, {"text": "current", "start": 225.519, "duration": 4.241}, {"text": "we need to relate that when the current", "start": 227.04, "duration": 6.399}, {"text": "i is equal to 10 amps", "start": 229.76, "duration": 6.479}, {"text": "so when the ammeter receives 10 amps", "start": 233.439, "duration": 5.201}, {"text": "we only want 200 microamps to flow", "start": 236.239, "duration": 5.041}, {"text": "through the galvanometer", "start": 238.64, "duration": 4.64}, {"text": "the rest of the current has to flow", "start": 241.28, "duration": 3.599}, {"text": "through the resistor", "start": 243.28, "duration": 3.12}, {"text": "so the majority of the current will flow", "start": 244.879, "duration": 3.761}, {"text": "there", "start": 246.4, "duration": 2.24}, {"text": "so ir", "start": 249.2, "duration": 4.16}, {"text": "is the difference between i", "start": 250.879, "duration": 4.08}, {"text": "and ig", "start": 253.36, "duration": 4.24}, {"text": "now notice that ig is very small", "start": 254.959, "duration": 6.56}, {"text": "so ir is approximately equal", "start": 257.6, "duration": 5.44}, {"text": "to the current that flows through the", "start": 261.519, "duration": 4.721}, {"text": "ammeter as a whole", "start": 263.04, "duration": 3.2}, {"text": "so what are we looking for in this", "start": 267.28, "duration": 4.639}, {"text": "problem what do we need to find", "start": 268.479, "duration": 3.44}, {"text": "we have the internal resistance", "start": 272.0, "duration": 5.68}, {"text": "so lowercase r is 10 ohms", "start": 274.32, "duration": 5.52}, {"text": "the only thing we need is to calculate", "start": 277.68, "duration": 4.959}, {"text": "the value of the shunt resistor", "start": 279.84, "duration": 3.52}, {"text": "r", "start": 282.639, "duration": 3.12}, {"text": "because once we have the right resistor", "start": 283.36, "duration": 4.0}, {"text": "then automatically it's just going to", "start": 285.759, "duration": 3.201}, {"text": "work", "start": 287.36, "duration": 3.36}, {"text": "so how can we calculate the value of r", "start": 288.96, "duration": 4.239}, {"text": "that we need", "start": 290.72, "duration": 2.479}, {"text": "notice that", "start": 293.759, "duration": 4.801}, {"text": "the galvanometer is in parallel", "start": 295.68, "duration": 5.44}, {"text": "with this resistor", "start": 298.56, "duration": 4.639}, {"text": "and so the voltage", "start": 301.12, "duration": 4.079}, {"text": "across the galvanometer let's say", "start": 303.199, "duration": 4.081}, {"text": "between points a and b is the same as", "start": 305.199, "duration": 4.56}, {"text": "the voltage across the resistor", "start": 307.28, "duration": 4.24}, {"text": "so we can say that the voltage across", "start": 309.759, "duration": 2.961}, {"text": "the resistor", "start": 311.52, "duration": 3.36}, {"text": "is equal to the voltage across the", "start": 312.72, "duration": 4.56}, {"text": "galvanometer", "start": 314.88, "duration": 6.08}, {"text": "now we know that v is equal to ir", "start": 317.28, "duration": 3.68}, {"text": "so the voltage across the resistor", "start": 321.199, "duration": 3.921}, {"text": "is the current that flows through the", "start": 323.84, "duration": 2.56}, {"text": "resistor", "start": 325.12, "duration": 3.519}, {"text": "times the resistor itself", "start": 326.4, "duration": 4.799}, {"text": "now the voltage across the galvanometer", "start": 328.639, "duration": 3.84}, {"text": "is the current that flows through the", "start": 331.199, "duration": 3.201}, {"text": "galvanometer times the internal", "start": 332.479, "duration": 3.121}, {"text": "resistance", "start": 334.4, "duration": 4.44}, {"text": "of the galvanometer", "start": 335.6, "duration": 3.24}, {"text": "now the only currents that we have", "start": 342.32, "duration": 4.08}, {"text": "is the current that's being measured and", "start": 344.56, "duration": 3.04}, {"text": "the current that flows through the", "start": 346.4, "duration": 2.639}, {"text": "galvanometer", "start": 347.6, "duration": 2.879}, {"text": "so it makes sense", "start": 349.039, "duration": 5.201}, {"text": "to replace ir with i minus ig", "start": 350.479, "duration": 5.44}, {"text": "so here's the main formula", "start": 354.24, "duration": 3.36}, {"text": "the current that flows through the", "start": 355.919, "duration": 2.881}, {"text": "ammeter", "start": 357.6, "duration": 2.64}, {"text": "minus the current that flows through the", "start": 358.8, "duration": 4.0}, {"text": "galvanometer that's ir", "start": 360.24, "duration": 5.36}, {"text": "times r that's equal to ig times", "start": 362.8, "duration": 5.44}, {"text": "lowercase r", "start": 365.6, "duration": 2.64}, {"text": "so now that we have the formula that we", "start": 368.479, "duration": 4.241}, {"text": "need let's calculate", "start": 370.0, "duration": 5.84}, {"text": "the shunt resistance", "start": 372.72, "duration": 3.12}, {"text": "so we know that i is equal to 1 amp", "start": 378.08, "duration": 6.399}, {"text": "actually 10 amps", "start": 382.0, "duration": 6.72}, {"text": "and then i g is 200 microamps", "start": 384.479, "duration": 7.121}, {"text": "and this is going to be times r", "start": 388.72, "duration": 6.44}, {"text": "let's get rid of this", "start": 391.6, "duration": 3.56}, {"text": "and then this is equal to ig which is", "start": 396.479, "duration": 4.641}, {"text": "200 microamps", "start": 398.56, "duration": 4.479}, {"text": "times the internal resistance", "start": 401.12, "duration": 5.32}, {"text": "of 10 ohms", "start": 403.039, "duration": 3.401}, {"text": "so micro is 10 to the minus six so this", "start": 408.88, "duration": 3.599}, {"text": "becomes 200", "start": 410.8, "duration": 4.88}, {"text": "times 10 to the minus six", "start": 412.479, "duration": 3.201}, {"text": "so on the left side", "start": 419.68, "duration": 3.44}, {"text": "ten minus two hundred times ten to the", "start": 421.199, "duration": 4.481}, {"text": "minus six", "start": 423.12, "duration": 2.56}, {"text": "that's nine point nine nine", "start": 426.08, "duration": 4.72}, {"text": "nine eight", "start": 428.319, "duration": 2.481}, {"text": "on the right side two hundred times ten", "start": 431.12, "duration": 5.12}, {"text": "to negative six times ten", "start": 432.96, "duration": 8.32}, {"text": "that's point zero zero two ohms", "start": 436.24, "duration": 6.64}, {"text": "and then so now we just gotta take point", "start": 441.28, "duration": 4.24}, {"text": "zero zero two divided by nine point nine", "start": 442.88, "duration": 5.439}, {"text": "nine nine eight", "start": 445.52, "duration": 3.76}, {"text": "you could", "start": 448.319, "duration": 3.201}, {"text": "make this 10 if you want", "start": 449.28, "duration": 4.16}, {"text": "so the answer is going to be about 2", "start": 451.52, "duration": 3.2}, {"text": "times 10", "start": 453.44, "duration": 4.56}, {"text": "to the negative 4 ohms", "start": 454.72, "duration": 3.28}, {"text": "so that's the shunt resistance", "start": 459.919, "duration": 4.56}, {"text": "that is needed to be in parallel with", "start": 462.08, "duration": 4.559}, {"text": "the galvanometer and as we said in the", "start": 464.479, "duration": 3.521}, {"text": "beginning", "start": 466.639, "duration": 4.24}, {"text": "the resistance of an ammeter ideally has", "start": 468.0, "duration": 5.52}, {"text": "to be very low we said approximately", "start": 470.879, "duration": 4.32}, {"text": "close to zero", "start": 473.52, "duration": 4.0}, {"text": "and for this one this is point zero zero", "start": 475.199, "duration": 5.44}, {"text": "zero two it's close to zero but it's not", "start": 477.52, "duration": 5.119}, {"text": "exactly zero", "start": 480.639, "duration": 3.84}, {"text": "so the shunt resistance has to be very", "start": 482.639, "duration": 5.68}, {"text": "very low in order for this to work", "start": 484.479, "duration": 5.041}, {"text": "number two", "start": 488.319, "duration": 3.44}, {"text": "design a voltmeter that can read 100", "start": 489.52, "duration": 4.0}, {"text": "volts at full scale", "start": 491.759, "duration": 3.521}, {"text": "using a galvanometer", "start": 493.52, "duration": 3.84}, {"text": "with a full scale sensitivity of 20", "start": 495.28, "duration": 3.68}, {"text": "microamps", "start": 497.36, "duration": 3.6}, {"text": "and with an internal resistance of 50", "start": 498.96, "duration": 3.12}, {"text": "ohms", "start": 500.96, "duration": 2.959}, {"text": "now in the last example we saw that an", "start": 502.08, "duration": 3.36}, {"text": "ammeter", "start": 503.919, "duration": 3.521}, {"text": "can be made from a galvanometer if the", "start": 505.44, "duration": 5.439}, {"text": "galvanometer is in parallel with a shunt", "start": 507.44, "duration": 4.8}, {"text": "resistor", "start": 510.879, "duration": 3.04}, {"text": "now to make a voltmeter", "start": 512.24, "duration": 4.479}, {"text": "the shunt resistor has to be in series", "start": 513.919, "duration": 4.401}, {"text": "with the galvanometer", "start": 516.719, "duration": 2.88}, {"text": "so we're going to have a circuit that", "start": 518.32, "duration": 2.88}, {"text": "looks like this", "start": 519.599, "duration": 5.041}, {"text": "so this is the shunt resistor", "start": 521.2, "duration": 3.44}, {"text": "and this is the internal resistance of", "start": 526.399, "duration": 3.761}, {"text": "the galvanometer", "start": 528.32, "duration": 5.36}, {"text": "so in blue we have the galvanometer", "start": 530.16, "duration": 4.88}, {"text": "combined", "start": 533.68, "duration": 4.32}, {"text": "this whole device makes the voltmeter", "start": 535.04, "duration": 4.88}, {"text": "which is represented by", "start": 538.0, "duration": 4.48}, {"text": "this symbol", "start": 539.92, "duration": 2.56}, {"text": "so the voltage across the voltmeter", "start": 543.279, "duration": 4.24}, {"text": "is the potential difference at these two", "start": 545.68, "duration": 4.159}, {"text": "points", "start": 547.519, "duration": 2.32}, {"text": "that voltage is equal to the current", "start": 551.44, "duration": 4.959}, {"text": "that flows through the circuit", "start": 554.24, "duration": 3.84}, {"text": "so that's the current going through the", "start": 556.399, "duration": 4.801}, {"text": "galvanometer which at full scale", "start": 558.08, "duration": 5.92}, {"text": "has to be 20 microamps", "start": 561.2, "duration": 5.52}, {"text": "so we know v equals ir and these two", "start": 564.0, "duration": 4.56}, {"text": "resistors are in series so the total", "start": 566.72, "duration": 3.28}, {"text": "resistance", "start": 568.56, "duration": 2.64}, {"text": "is the sum", "start": 570.0, "duration": 3.44}, {"text": "of the shunt resistor", "start": 571.2, "duration": 4.0}, {"text": "and", "start": 573.44, "duration": 4.48}, {"text": "the internal resistance", "start": 575.2, "duration": 4.96}, {"text": "now because this value is going to be so", "start": 577.92, "duration": 4.56}, {"text": "small compared to this value", "start": 580.16, "duration": 5.28}, {"text": "we can say that r plus r", "start": 582.48, "duration": 4.96}, {"text": "is approximately", "start": 585.44, "duration": 3.519}, {"text": "capital r", "start": 587.44, "duration": 3.44}, {"text": "i'm going to use the exact equation for", "start": 588.959, "duration": 3.681}, {"text": "this problem", "start": 590.88, "duration": 3.6}, {"text": "now in this problem we want the volt", "start": 592.64, "duration": 4.0}, {"text": "meter to read 100 volts", "start": 594.48, "duration": 4.32}, {"text": "when the current of 20 microamps passes", "start": 596.64, "duration": 3.52}, {"text": "through it", "start": 598.8, "duration": 3.92}, {"text": "so let's replace v with 100 and let's", "start": 600.16, "duration": 5.119}, {"text": "replace the current with 20", "start": 602.72, "duration": 6.4}, {"text": "times 10 to the minus 6 amps", "start": 605.279, "duration": 3.841}, {"text": "and lowercase r that's", "start": 610.24, "duration": 6.159}, {"text": "the internal resistance of 50 ohms", "start": 612.8, "duration": 6.08}, {"text": "so first let's divide 100", "start": 616.399, "duration": 6.241}, {"text": "by 20 times 10 to the minus six", "start": 618.88, "duration": 7.519}, {"text": "and so that's going to equal 5 million", "start": 622.64, "duration": 6.16}, {"text": "and so that's r plus 50.", "start": 626.399, "duration": 4.961}, {"text": "if we take 5 million and subtract it by", "start": 628.8, "duration": 4.56}, {"text": "50.", "start": 631.36, "duration": 4.4}, {"text": "the exact value of r is going to be", "start": 633.36, "duration": 3.76}, {"text": "4 million", "start": 635.76, "duration": 4.72}, {"text": "999 000 and 950.", "start": 637.12, "duration": 5.2}, {"text": "now when selecting a resistor on the", "start": 640.48, "duration": 3.599}, {"text": "practical circumstances you're not going", "start": 642.32, "duration": 4.32}, {"text": "to find in the resistor that is four", "start": 644.079, "duration": 3.841}, {"text": "million nine hundred ninety thousand", "start": 646.64, "duration": 3.12}, {"text": "nine fifty instead you're gonna have to", "start": 647.92, "duration": 5.44}, {"text": "use a five mega ohm resistor", "start": 649.76, "duration": 5.759}, {"text": "so now you know how to calculate", "start": 653.36, "duration": 3.76}, {"text": "the shunt resistor", "start": 655.519, "duration": 4.88}, {"text": "to turn a galvanometer into an ammeter", "start": 657.12, "duration": 4.64}, {"text": "or a voltmeter", "start": 660.399, "duration": 3.841}, {"text": "so just keep this in mind", "start": 661.76, "duration": 4.8}, {"text": "to turn", "start": 664.24, "duration": 6.56}, {"text": "a galvanometer into an ammeter", "start": 666.56, "duration": 4.24}, {"text": "the galvanometer has to be", "start": 671.6, "duration": 7.2}, {"text": "parallel to the shunt resistor", "start": 675.2, "duration": 3.6}, {"text": "and to calculate the shunt resistor", "start": 680.24, "duration": 3.599}, {"text": "it's going to be the current that flows", "start": 682.32, "duration": 3.28}, {"text": "through the galvanometer times the", "start": 683.839, "duration": 3.601}, {"text": "internal resistance", "start": 685.6, "duration": 4.56}, {"text": "divided by", "start": 687.44, "duration": 2.72}, {"text": "the current that flows in the circuit", "start": 691.92, "duration": 4.32}, {"text": "minus", "start": 694.64, "duration": 3.28}, {"text": "the current flowing through the", "start": 696.24, "duration": 3.92}, {"text": "galvanometer", "start": 697.92, "duration": 4.8}, {"text": "so that's how you can calculate it", "start": 700.16, "duration": 5.52}, {"text": "and for the voltmeter", "start": 702.72, "duration": 2.96}, {"text": "just remember that the shunt resistor", "start": 710.399, "duration": 3.921}, {"text": "has to be in series", "start": 712.48, "duration": 4.479}, {"text": "with the galvanometer", "start": 714.32, "duration": 4.8}, {"text": "and so to calculate", "start": 716.959, "duration": 3.841}, {"text": "the resistance it's going to be the", "start": 719.12, "duration": 2.88}, {"text": "voltage", "start": 720.8, "duration": 3.279}, {"text": "across these two points", "start": 722.0, "duration": 4.0}, {"text": "that is across", "start": 724.079, "duration": 4.481}, {"text": "point a and b", "start": 726.0, "duration": 4.959}, {"text": "divided by", "start": 728.56, "duration": 4.8}, {"text": "the current that flows to it", "start": 730.959, "duration": 5.281}, {"text": "and then minus the internal resistance", "start": 733.36, "duration": 4.479}, {"text": "but chances are you could ignore this r", "start": 736.24, "duration": 3.44}, {"text": "value but i'm going to put it there", "start": 737.839, "duration": 3.68}, {"text": "so that's how you can calculate the", "start": 739.68, "duration": 3.36}, {"text": "shunt resistor", "start": 741.519, "duration": 4.32}, {"text": "for a voltmeter", "start": 743.04, "duration": 2.799}, {"text": "you", "start": 765.36, "duration": 2.08}]